vectorData.altText: IDENTIFY, again, in the prosected female hemi-pelvis, the ovary.

Identify its suspensory ligament, the ligament of the ovary and the round ligament. GENTLY pull the fallopian tube superiorly, and confirm the position of the ovary on the posterior surface of the broad ligament.
To review the anatomy of the ovaries and fallopian tubes, click here:

IDENTIFY, again, in the prosected female hemi-pelvis, the uterine tubes     . Notice their course from the superolateral aspect of the uterus laterally, within the superior margin of the broad ligament. Observe that the uterine tube terminates lateral to the ovary, and so turns back to meet its surface.
IDENTIFY the expanded infundibulum of the uterine tube and its fimbriae. Realize that the uterine tube opens into the peritoneal cavity, and that eggs released by the ovary must be drawn into the lumen of the uterine tube. The most common site of fertilization is in the ampulla of the uterine tube; the conceptus then passing along its isthmus and intramural portion to access the uterine cavity.

In the female embryo, the gubernaculum connects the female gonad to the labium majus, the female homologue of the scrotum. The remnants of the gubernaculum in the female are the ligament of the ovary and the round ligament, the latter passing through the inguinal canal to the labium majus.
The uterine tubes      extend laterally from the superolateral aspect of the uterus. The uterine tubes are end as the expanded infundibulum of the uterine tube with its fimbriae. The uterine tube opens into the peritoneal cavity, and eggs released by the ovary must be drawn into the lumen of the uterine tube. The most common site of fertilization is in the ampulla of the uterine tube; the conceptus then passing along its isthmus and intramural portion to access the uterine cavity.

In the embryo, the ovaries originate high up in the posterior abdominal wall, and that they migrate, prenatally, to their ultimate position in the pelvis. This is analogous to the descent of the testes in the male, although the ovaries do not migrate into the perineum.
Ovarian nerves, vessels and lymphatics are located in the suspensory ligament of the ovary, and travel back, through the posterior abdominal wall, to the embryonic level of origin of the ovaries.
